So it's totally not their fault that they set up a situation where:
1. All tribes have to prioritize funding in the same way
2. Tribes have to arbitrarily prioritize 7 areas. Do we prioritize healthcare, education, etc or language? Limited choices is a tool of colonialism.

ALSO, the only funding source that is mandatory to tribes - Bureau of Indian Affairs funding - "culture" is not an allowable expense? You might think it's cause of the BIA making an arbitrary rule, but NO! They told tribes to prioritize 7 funding areas for the BIA...

How many tribal languages are out there? Hundreds at least. How many tribes get funded by the ANA every year? Go find out...cause it isn't even a hundred. If I remember correctly, in 2020 it was less than 20 grantees.

That is the Administration for Native Americans Martinez Immersion and Language Development grants. I have worked on many federal and non-federal grants over the last 5 years and the ANA grant is one of the most onerous. This is a barrier to tribes without grant writing depts.

Also, for folks who don't know...despite vast government programs such as Boarding Schools that actively tried to destroy our languages, the Federal Government only has one. ONE. fund specifically for Native languages.

If you've ever talked with me about Language funding, you'll know that my stance is that the Federal government must spend on Language revitalization what they spent on language destruction. Once we reach that level THEN we can discuss what is fair moving forward.

And like…am I missing something? Does “Indian Removal” categorically refer to removal of the 5 Tribes? If so, what words are we using that encompasses that as well as the rampant removal that happened during and following the Civil War.
It’s - and I can’t stress this enough - really important that we connect the various forms of genocidal removal used by the United States and other colonial powers.
